Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
createPinGuide(25.10)                                    createPinGuide(25.10)

Name
       createPinGuide - Creates a pin guide object

Syntax
        createPinGuide

       [-help]

       {[  -area  {<x1  y1 x2 y2>} | [-edge <integer> [[-offset_start <float>]
       [-offset_end <float>]]]][ -layer {<layeridList>} [-layerPriority ]]}

        [-pin <string> |  -pinGroup  <string>  |  -net  <string>  |  -netGroup
       <string> | -name <string> ]

        [-edge <integer> | -net <string> | -netGroup <string>]

        [-cell <string> | -net <string> | -netGroup <string>]

       Creates a pin guide object. The pin guide restricts the pins associated
       with  the pin guide within the specified area. You can run this command
       on the top-level module also. You can assign the same pin group or  net
       group to multiple pin guides. Pin guides are generated for buses, nets,
       net groups, pins, and pin groups. For buses and nets that do not physi-
       cally connect to the partition, pin guides will not be created. You can
       use this command during partition floorplanning.

Parameters
       -area <x1 y1 x2 y2>
              Specifies the coordinates of the pin guide area.

              * x1:  Specifies  the  lower  left x coordinate of the pin guide
                area.

              * y1: Specifies the lower left y coordinate  of  the  pin  guide
                area.

              * x2:  Specifies  the  upper right x coordinate of the pin guide
                area.

              * y2: Specifies the upper right y coordinate of  the  pin  guide
                area.

              Data_type: rect, required

       -cell <string>
              Specifies  the  name of the cell. This parameter is not required
              if you are using the command for a top-level module.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -edge <integer>
              Specifies the integer value where  edge  numbering  starts  from
              lower-left  corner of a partition clock-wise. Edge 0 is the edge
              that has the smallest y value.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes type and  default  in-
              formation  for each createPinGuide parameter. For a detailed de-
              scription of the command and all of its parameters, use the  man
              command:

              man createPinGuide.

       -layer {<layerIdList>}
              Specifies the metal layer(s) for the pin guide.

              Default:  You  must specify the correct pin layer. If you do not
              specify the pin layer, Innovus will display an error instead  of
              choosing  the preferred layer to assign pins like the old behav-
              ior.

              Note: Pins will not be assigned on  non-preferred  layers.  How-
              ever,  pins can be assigned on Metal1 layer if the ptnAssignPin-
              sOnLayerM1 global variable is set to 1.

              Note: Layers can be specified using the LEF layer names or layer
              ID numbers.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -layerPriority
              Assign pins based on the order of -layer specified by the user.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -name <string >
              Specifies the name of the partition pin  guide  object.  If  you
              specify  this  parameter,  the command will automatically detect
              whether the object is a pin, pin group, net, net group, or  bus.
              In case there are different objects with the same name, the com-
              mand selects the object with the following precedence:

              * If  a  cell  name is specified, the command selects the object
                with the following precedence:

              *

                * pin

                * pin group

                * net

                * net group or bus

              * If a cell name is not specified, the command selects  the  ob-
                ject with the following precedence:

              *

                * net

                * net group or bus

              For  example,  if  the value of objectName is P1, and there is a
              pin group named P1 as well as a bus named P1, the  command  will
              select the pin group named P1.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -net <string>
              For  nets,  specifies  the name of the net. For buses, specifies
              the name of the bus or the bus radix.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -netGroup <string>
              Specifies the name of the net group.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -offset_end <float>
              Specifies the distance, in microns, from the  ending  corner  of
              the edge.

              Minimum Value: 0

              Maximum Value: 65535

              Data_type: float, optional

       -offset_start <float>
              Specifies  the distance, in microns, from the starting corner of
              the edge.

              Minimum Value: 0

              Maximum Value: 65535

              Data_type: float, optional

       -pin <string>
              Specifies the name of the pin.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -pinGroup <string>
              Specifies the name of the pin group.

              Default: By default the name is defRGuideName.

              Data_type: string, optional

Example
              * The following command creates a pin guide object for bus addr:

                createPinGuide -area 2353.8000  7123.000  2653.8000  8298.2000
                -name addr

Related Information
